<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Association of Community Rail Partnerships (ACoRP) (TIC 056)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> the Association of Community Rail Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> (ACoRP) (TIC 056)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">0 stations, many on lines supported by Community Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> serve isolated communities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Partnerships work effectively to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">use of the lines and to improve services to isolated communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  They</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> mak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> extensive use of voluntary support from the local community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and effectively break dow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">n the silo thinking that can inhibit improvements where a number of agencies are involved.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Recent local government budget reductions have limited or removed support from some partnerships and it is proving increasingly difficult to continue the good wor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">k.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Giving local authorities a statutory duty (and the resources) to encourage rail services to isolated communities would help the survival and continuation of the Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and the benefits they bring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A very small number of lines have service levels t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">oo low to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">provide a realistic service to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">meet the varie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> travel needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> they serve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  The normal criteria for allocation of resources should, by exception, be revised to allow these lines to meet more of the demand than is currently </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">possible.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The programme to improve accessibility at stations with low platforms should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">continu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ed to cover all those serving isolated communities  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ACoRP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ACoRP is the body representing community rail partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(CRPs) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and station support groups thr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oughout the country.  It has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">39</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> CRP members covering 7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lines and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">122</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> station support groups.  It provides training and supports research into the potential and benefits of applying community rail principles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (described below)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, disseminates good practice and manages two grant schemes which provide encouragement and support for community projects that bring benefits to the lines concerned.   It also monitors the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">passenger numbers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of community rail lines with the cooperation of A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">TOC, to identify trends and the benefits flowing from initiatives promoted by CRPs</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Railways serving Isolated Communities</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many community rail lines and services run through predominantly rural areas, and some stations serve isolated communities.  There are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2520 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stations on the national rail network, of which 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">192</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are small, unstaffed stations (Category F), and of these, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">694 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have less than 100,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> journeys a year.  A smaller subset</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of 63</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, flagged by ORR as small stations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are listed at Appendix A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, of which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">40 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">serve isolated communities.  Throughout the country, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">170</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> stations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">serve isolated communities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> examples of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">throughout Britain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are given in Appendix B.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Community Rail Partnerships</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many of the rail routes that serv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e isolated rural communities are supported by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CRP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A number of these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lines run through exceptional scenery, serve national parks and smaller coastal resorts.  The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">key to renewing and strengthening the economy of these areas in a sustainable way.  They bring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tourists and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">provide essential journeys for local people.  They also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">encourage walking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd provide car free access to sensitive rural areas.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Partnerships have been very successful in increasing rail ridership and engaging with local communities.  They bring together a number of disparate interests </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who have an interest in the success of their local railway.  The core membership includes the loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l transport planning authority (county or unitary councils in England), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the train operator and the rail user group.  Other members may include district, town or parish councils, Network Rail, National Parks, universities or heritage railways.  A wide spect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rum of supporters are drawn from local people, amenity groups, the Womens’ Institute, local traders and indeed anyone who wants to see improvements to their railway.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CRPs are typically run by a paid partnership officer, usually employed by the local author</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ity, sometimes on a part time basis.  Much of the financial support for promoting the lines</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and making minor improvements comes from train operators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the tourism sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and (until recently) from local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  The work is mainly done by volunteers, fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">om </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">customer service and leaflet distribution to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">landscaping, station gardens and running special events such as music trains.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In particular, volunteers provide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ideas and are ambassadors for the railway within their communities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The value of time of the volunteers supporting CRPs has been estimated at £27m a year.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Authority Support</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Over the 20 years since the start of CRPs, a huge amount has been achieved at very low cost.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The average benefit to cost ratio of a community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rail scheme is 4.6:1.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Now, however, pressure of local authority spending has caused most to reduce their financial support, and some to withdraw support altogether.  This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> caus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">serious </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">problems for some partnerships and while a lot can be achieve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> little money, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nothing can be done</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if no money is available.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst local authorities appreciate the value of community rail and have supported it where they can, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> spending on rail is vulnerable to cuts because it is discretionary.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local au</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">thorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are not responsible for the provision of local rail services, and while they may want to support further rail development, given its proven record of success, it is optional, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is always the risk that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will be moved to pay for thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r primary statutory responsibilities such as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> social services or highway maintenance.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ACoRP believes that it would be helpful if this position changed, and local authorities were given a statutory responsibility to ensure local rail services are adequate to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> meet the needs of local people together with funding to enable them to carry out this responsibility. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Accessibility – platform stepping distances</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At some stations serving isolated communities access is more difficult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as the stepping distance from the platform to the train is too great for older passengers or those with disabilities to manage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and where the cost of raising platform heights can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">high (sometimes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in excess of £0.25m. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">per platform).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Here the solution is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to provide a short section of raised platform that can be transported to site relatively easily and bolted down to improve access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, known generally as the ‘Harrington hump’ after its first application in Cumbria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Network Rail’s ‘Alternative Route Utilisati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on strategy’ identified some 300 stations that would benefit from humps, and funding for a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> programme of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">100 was agreed with DfT in 2011.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oRP believes that the programme should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">continue until it has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">embrace</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> all stations with sub</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">standard stepping </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">distances, which would bring particular benefits to those serving isolated communities.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Questions R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">aised by the Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities (including rural and urban </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">areas and island communities?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In relation to buses in England, this is left to the market to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">determine, with local authorities having powers to support non commercial services or to support community transport where they contribute to solving local transport problems, including social isolation.  In relation to local rail services, the level of se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rvice is determined by the Department for Transport which specifies the franchise requirement.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Local authorities are able to support additional local train services but are frequently constrained from doing so by the reduction in rate support grant by cen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">tral government and the inadequate remit on the provision of local rail services described above.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 34.34pt; padding-left:1.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g. people with disabilities, older people, young people) taken into account in determining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 20.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The railway </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">has responded well in recent years </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to the needs of different groups of passengers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, and this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> brings benefits to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in isolated communities as well as those in more populous areas.  For example, all new trains are built to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">meet the requirements of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the Rail Vehicle Accessibilit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">y Regulations, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">1998</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  Even those that are not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">yet </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">fully compliant are generally accessible and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the increasing number of holders of Disabled Persons Railcard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is evidence of the success of the policy of steadily improving accessibility over a period of 30 years. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Accessibility at some stations serving isolated communities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">is being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> improved through u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">se of the ‘Harrington hump’ (see above.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 20.95pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Young people and older passengers benefit from the various railcards available which offer discounted fares.  On </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a number of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> routes serving isolated communities, the benefits are extended to all passengers who hold the local line railcard.  Most of these cards have been introduced as a result of the initiative of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">CRP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A few e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">xamples are:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 100.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Cotswold Line railcard (Oxford to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Worcester and Hereford)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Devon &amp; Cornwall railcard </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 100.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Esk Valley Line railcard (Midd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">esbrough to Whitby)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 100.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Heart of Wales Line railcard (Swansea to Shrewsbury)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">services to isolated communiti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es? How can these challenges be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overcome?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">One challenge on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a few rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> routes is to be able to offer a frequency of service adequate to meet the various needs of people in the communities it serves.  A few rural railway routes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">offer a service of just four trains a day each way, which limits </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">journey </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">opportunities.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The lines concerned are:</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 99.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Esk Valley line (Middlesbrough – Whitby)</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 99.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Heart of Wales line (Swansea – Lland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">overy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> – Shrewsbury)</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 99.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Bentham line (Morecambe - Skipton – Leeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">)</span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In the case of Esk Valley, for example, the timetable is built around the need to bring schoolchildren to Whitby from the villages along the Esk Valley, and to bring in day trip visi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ors to Whitby on Sundays.  (The permanent Sunday service results from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the initiative of the CRP).  It cannot meet other demands, such as travel to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">work from Whitby to Middlesbrough, for example, or for longer day trips from the line to Leeds or London.  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">These limited services were introduced by BR many years ago as part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a resource-led timetable to save money, but have become embedded in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">franchise specifications.  They severely limit the journey opportunities possible by rail and a great deal more could be achieved with a higher frequency.  As the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> lines</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> serve isolated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">communities, demand levels will always be lower than those on the busier suburban or interurban routes which will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">always show better value for money in any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">competition for resources</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  However, as these lines are few in number and atypical, AcoRP </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">would argue that funding and rolling st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ock should be made available</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, exceptionally,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">improve services to the rural communities they serve, at least on a trial basis.  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A number of long rural routes serving isolated commun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ties in Scotland also have just </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">three or four trains a day, but a positive example of tackling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">is currently planned</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> on the West Highland line between Glasgow and Oban.  Here, through skil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ful timetabling and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">diagramming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> of the Scotrail fleet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> it will be possible to double the frequency between the junction at Cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">anlarich and Oban from three to six trains a day by using just one additional two-car train.  The additional cost of this is being met by Transport Scotland, but the benefits to passen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">gers are widespread</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> providing new journey opportunities, better ferry connections </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to the islands </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and a link with the Fort William to London sleeper.     </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nities? How could Community Transport be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Because of its flexibility and frequent use of accessible vehicles, Community Transport organisations can provide services that are tailored very specifically to local needs, offering a cost-effective tran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sport option in rural areas.  Furthermore, their not-for-profit status and close links with the communities they serve meet the government’s localism agenda admirably.  However, as with CRP’s, reductions in local authority funding and other sources of inco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">me, such as BSOG, are putting the long-term future of many of these groups in doubt.  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">There is no doubt that closer integration of community transport operations with community rail routes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ould be of significant benefit to rural communities and could off</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">er greater value for money across the board.  Several Community Rail Partnerships are already experimenting with minibus links to and from their local stations and these are proving successful. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Similarly, the Heart of Wales Line partnership runs minibuses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to bring people from the train to visit tourist attractions in the isolated communities along its route.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It is our view however that wider introduction of this concept could only be achieved with proper financial support and encouragement through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">modifying competition legislation.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ACoRP fully supports community transport operations, and maintains contact with the Community Transport Association, although they are not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">direct</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ly within our remit. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">E. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To what extent should passengers in isolated commun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport services?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Rail is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">high volume</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> transport mode </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> even the smallest train of one coach has a seating capacity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">75 p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">assengers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, so inevitably, some isolated communities will be bett</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">er served by demand responsive transport services, including cars and bicycles.  The important point then is to ensure an easy transfer at the railhead with adequate car parking, secure cycle storage and good interchange </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> bus, taxi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> community transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">In general, deep rural areas have few taxis available and fares will inevitably be high, simply because of the distances to be covered.  Accessibility and the cost of living in rural areas remains a deep-seated problem, and the cost of a taxi fare will fre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">quently outweigh the ability of someone to pay. In an urban environment, the taxi </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">be an affordable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">option, whereas for rural dwellers it becomes more often a distressed purchase.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">F. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What are the main challenges associated with funding transport servic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es in isolated communities? How can these services be made more affordable?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">With its own infrastructure and high safety and accessibility standards, rail is a relatively expensive mode, although costs are being reduced through the regulated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">settlement for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Control Period 4 involving a reduction in Network Rail costs of around a third.  At the same time, reducing franchising payments or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">increasing premia for train operators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mean that train operators </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in aggregate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">now net contributors to Government, rather </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">than a net</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> cost to the taxpayer.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he principles of community rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">development have enabled costs savings to be made (for example the Harrington hump) but community r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">il lines are generally run with minimal resources and the scope for significant further r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">eduction of cost is limited.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">However, CRPs are very effective in increasing ridership which reduces the subsidy per passenger kilometre and so increases the value for money to the taxpayer of the service provided.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Heart of Wales Line Forum is actively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> investigating whether some form of local management of their long route can be used to enhance services at low cost. They aim to have a scheme in place in time for the implementation of the new Wales and Borders franchise in 2018. They have the active sup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">port of Welsh Government, ORR and ACoRP in this.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Appendix A</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:center; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">63</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">mall Stations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">listed by the Office of Rail Regulation</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Stations within Community Rail Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">+</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Stations in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urban areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span